full_text:
When I got my Novice license in 1967 I mainly hung out on 40 and 15 
meters.  Didn&#39;t have an antenna that worked on 80 meters (or so I 
thought). I&#39;ve since learned that any piece of wire can be tuned to 80 
meters and some of them actually radiate!
:-)

I&#39;m curious about this 1485 kHz frequency.  And I was surprised the FCC 
website I listed would come up with so many foreign stations on 1480 and 
1490. Lots of interesting data from that website.  Trans World Radio in 
Bonaire on 800 kHz runs 500 kW - that&#39;s half a million watts!

Zack (W9SZ)


On Thu, 20 Nov 2008, threadsintyme@... wrote:

&gt; Zack,
&gt; You&#39;re quite right...I was thinking of 15 meters. Hung out on 20 and 40 meters respectively.
&gt; Al
&gt;
&gt; -- Zack Widup &lt;w9sz@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Hi Al,
&gt;
&gt; Do you mean the 14 MHz (20 meter) band or 21 MHz (15 meter) band? 14
&gt; meters was never allocated to radio amateurs. :-)
&gt;
&gt; Until we get some more sunspots, 15 meters and above has been fairly dead
&gt; for over a year. 20 meters has quite a bit of activity and 40 and 80
&gt; meters get most of the activity these days.
&gt;
&gt; 1485 kHz is in the AM broadcast band but isn&#39;t a standard channel in the
&gt; USA, which goes in 10 kHz steps. There would be stations on 1480 and 1490
&gt; in the USA, not necesssarily in your area, though. If you go to this page:
&gt;
&gt; http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/amq.html
&gt;
&gt; Enter 1480 as the lower frequency and 1490 as the upper frequency and
&gt; you&#39;ll get a page listing all the stations on those two frequencies.
&gt;
&gt; Zack
&gt;
&gt; On Wed, 19 Nov 2008, threadsintyme@... wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; LOL...Same here! I *thought* that this sounded as if it were in the AM band.
&gt;&gt; Glad I didn&#39;t ask if it was AM or FM or SSB! LOL hehe
&gt;&gt; Man, I remember when I was a kid and would work DX on the 14 meter band. CW was my choice and really loved it. &lt;sigh, heavy, heart broken sigh&gt;
&gt;&gt; That was back in the good ole daze of 1968...had more sick days at school that they kept up with!
&gt;&gt; Al
